Introduction to ggplot2

Muhammad Hilmi Abdul Majid

Introduction

In the previous topic, we have used base R to produce visuals, figures, and plots without additional packages. In this topic, we will start introducing and using ggplot2, an R package that is used by many data analyst, to produce visuals.

What is ggplot2?

Data visualization is an essential tool for understanding and communicating complex data effectively. In R, one of the most powerful and popular libraries for creating stunning visualizations is ggplot2. Created by Hadley Wickham, ggplot2 is based on the principles of “The Grammar of Graphics,” a coherent system for describing and building visualizations. To learn more about this package, you can visit http://ggplot2.org/.

As mentioned, ggplot2 is based on the grammar of graphics, which splits a plot or visual into different parts:

Plot = Data + Aesthetics + Geometry

  • Data refers to the data frame or dataset.

  • Aesthetics refers to the x and y variables that will be used to draw the plot. The x and y variables are from the data.

  • Geometry refers to the type of graphics used to draw the plot. For example, it can be a scatterplot, box plot, bar chart, and so on.

Why use ggplot2?

Why use ggplot2 over base R graphics? There are several reasons as mentioned below.

  • Grammar of graphics framework:

    • ggplot2 is built on the grammar of graphics, which provides a structured and consistent approach to creating plots. This framework allows users to build plots layer by layer, making it easy to add or modify elements (e.g., layers for data points, smoothed lines, text annotations). or to experiment with and customize visualizations incrementally.

    • Base R graphics lack this systematic layering approach, making it harder to modify existing plots.

  • Nicer plots:

    • ggplot2 has better default aesthetics, producing polished and publication-quality plots right out of the box.

    • Base R graphics often require significant tweaking to achieve the same level of polish, especially for color schemes, legends, and axis formatting.

  • Data handling:

    • ggplot2 works seamlessly with data frames and tidy data, which is the standard in modern data analysis. This makes it easier to create plots directly from datasets without pre-processing or restructuring the data.

    • Base R graphics require more manual data manipulation before plotting.

  • Customization and complexity:

    • With ggplot2, it is straightforward to create complex and multi-faceted visualizations (e.g., faceted plots, layered charts, and complex combinations of plot types).

    • While base R graphics can achieve similar results, it often requires additional libraries (e.g., lattice) or significantly more effort to code.

  • Consistency:

    • In ggplot2, the syntax is consistent across different types of plots, as it relies on layering and mapping aesthetics like aes(x, y) and geom_. This makes it easier for users to learn and apply.

    • Base R graphics use different functions (e.g., plot(), barplot(), hist(), boxplot()) for different types of visualizations, each with its own syntax and quirks.

  • Extensions and community support:

    • ggplot2 is part of the tidyverse, a collection of R packages designed to work together. It integrates smoothly with other tools like dplyr and tidyr.

    • A large ecosystem of extensions (e.g., ggplotly, ggraph, gganimate) builds on ggplot2, allowing users to create interactive and animated visualizations easily.

    • Base R graphics do not have the same level of extensibility or integration.

Note however, that at the end of the day, it depends on the individuals themselves whether they prefer to use base R graphics, or ggplot2.

When to use base R graphics?

Base R graphics may still be useful for quick exploratory data analysis, especially for:

  • Simple plots where customization is unnecessary.

  • Situations where you need highly specific or non-standard customization, which might be more direct in base R.

For most cases, however, ggplot2 is preferred due to its power, flexibility, and ease of use.

A Quick Example on ggplot2

Before we start using ggplot2, we have to first install the package and load it.

# Download the ggplot2 package for the current R version
# Run once per R version
install.packages("ggplot2")

# Load the downloaded files
# Run once per session if you want to use ggplot2
library(ggplot2)

The graphs produced using ggplot2 are built in layers. You start with a simple graph and you add layers on top of the graphs, until you are satisfied with it.

For this section of the topic, we will use the gapminder dataset from the gapminder package. To make it easy, we will further select only data from 1997 and 2007. You can check the help page for the dataset by running ?gapminder or help(gapminder) after installing and loading the package.

install.packages("gapminder")  # Run once per R version
library(gapminder)             # Run once per session
library(dplyr)                 # Run once per session, to use filter

gm_df <- filter(gapminder, year %in% c(1997,2007))
head(gm_df)

ggplot

The first function to built a graph using ggplot2 is the ggplot() function. This function is used to specify the data and the aesthetic (the x and y variable used for the graph).

Let’s try running ggplot() without any argument.

ggplot()

As you can see, it produces a plot with a background. But there is no axes and no data point in the figure.

Next, let us specify the data using data=gm_df argument and set the x-axis to be gdpPercap and y-axis to be lifeExp from the dataset by using the argument mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp). The mapping for the x and y axes uses the aes() function.

ggplot(data = gm_df, mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp))

As we can see, we now have the x and y axes. But the plot is still empty as we have not specified what kind of plot we want.

Geometric objects

The geoms are geometric objects (points, lines, and so on) that is placed on a graph. In ggplot2, the functions for geoms start with geom_. For example, geom_point() is used to add points in the graph, and geom_line() is used to add lines. For this example, we will use geom_points() to create a scatterplot.

To add the selected geoms to the graph, we chain the ggplot() function written before with the geom_ function with a + sign.

ggplot(data = gm_df,                                # Data is gm_df
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +     # Specify x and y
  geom_point()                                      # Add points to the plot

As you can see, now we have points in the plot and have produced a scatterplot.

There are options you can use when calling the geom_ function. For geom_point(), some of the options are color, size and shape. You can check these by running help(geom_point) or ?geom_point. Note that for the shape argument, you can use characters such as "o" or numbers, as shown in previous topic for scatterplot.

ggplot(data = gm_df,                                # Data is gm_df
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +     # Specify x and y
  geom_point(color="indianred3", size=2, shape=1)   # Add points to the plot

If you want to add another geom object on the plot, you just have to chain another geom_ function with a + sign.

ggplot(data = gm_df,                                 # Data is gm_df
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +      # Specify x and y
  geom_point(color="indianred3", size=2, shape=1) +  # Add points to the plot
  geom_smooth() +                                    # Add smooth line
  geom_hline(yintercept = 70, linetype = 2)          # Add horizontal line

Mapping of different color, shape and size

The mapping argument in ggplot() can also be used modify the color, shape, size, and other characteristics for the data. To do that, you need to add extra arguments in the aes() function. In the code below, we change the color based on the country’s continent, and the size of the points by the country’s population.

ggplot(data = gm_df,                          # Data is gm_df
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp,  # Specify x and y
                     color=continent,         # Color of data by continent
                     size=pop)) +             # Make the size depends on pop
  geom_point()                                # Add points in plot

Note that the color argument in the aes() function is very useful if you want to show different groups of data in the plot.

You can also use shape argument in the aes() function to group the data.

ggplot(data = gm_df,                          # Data is gm_df
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp,  # Specify x and y
                     shape=continent,         # Shape of data by continent
                     color=continent)) +      # Color of data point by continent
  geom_point()                                # Add points in plot

When the mapping in aes() is included in the ggplot() function, it becomes the global mapping for the plot. However, we can also use the mapping inside of the geom_ function to have individual mapping. This can be useful if we want to further customize the shape, color, and so on.

ggplot(data = gm_df,                                # Data is gm_df
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp,        # Specify x and y
                     color=continent)) +            # Color of data point by continent
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color=as.factor(year)))  # Add points in plot in indianred3 color

Notice that the individual mapping overlaps with the global mapping regarding the color of data points. In this case, the individual mapping takes priority and is used. However, the title of the legend for the color follows the global mapping.

Scales

For each aesthetic, the scales are used to control how variables are used in the plot. We can modify the scale by adding scale functions of the form scale_ and chain it using the + sign. For example, for the scatterplot of life expectation vs GDP per capita before, we might want to use a log scale for the GDP per capita, and use scale_x_log10() in our code.

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point() +
  
  # Scale the x-axis by log10
  scale_x_log10()

Notice the change in the x-axis in the figure above. If we also want to include currency in the x-axis label, we can add another argument to the scale_x_log10() function.

# Load scales package for label_currency() function
# Otherwise, you need to use 'scales::label_currency()'
library(scales)

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point() +
  
  # Change the x axis to log10 scale with currency label
  scale_x_log10(labels = label_currency()) +
  
  # or (same result)
  # scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_currency(), trans="log10") +
  
  # Change the tick marks on the y-axis
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(30,100,by=5))

Facets

Facets are used split the data into groups or subsets and draw graph for each of them separately. To create facets, we can add the facet_ function into the chain. There are two facet_ functions in ggplot2. First is facet_wrap which uses the formula object as the argument, and groups the data based on the specified formula.

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  
  facet_wrap(~continent)

Second is the facet_grid() function, that creates a grid-like output with specified variables for rows and columns.

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  
  facet_grid(rows=vars(continent), cols=vars(year))

Title, subtitle, and axis labels

To add title, subtitle and custom labels for the x and y axes, we can add the labs() function to the chain. Here are some of the main arguments for the labs() function.

  • title: Add title to the plot.

  • subtitle: Add subtitle to the plot.

  • x, y: The x and y axis labels.

  • caption: Add caption to the plot

  • color, shape, size: The title for the legends for color, shape and size (if used).

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  facet_wrap(~year) +
  
  labs(title = "Economic Growth and Life Expectancy", # Title of the plot
       subtitle = "Does it get better?",              # Subtitle
       x = "GDP Per Capita in USD",                   # x-axis label
       y = "Life Expectancy in Years",                # y-axis label
       color = "Continent",                           # Legend for colors
       caption = "Source: Gapminder")                 # Caption

Themes

Another useful feature of ggplot2 are the themes. Themes control the colors, fonts, and other visual properties of a plot. To use the theme functions, we simply add another theme_ function to the chain. The ggplot2 comes with eight different themes: theme_grey(), theme_bw(), theme_linedraw(), theme_light(), theme_dark(), theme_minimal(), theme_classic(), theme_void() .

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(color="indianred3") +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(title = "Economic Growth and Life Expectancy",
       subtitle = "Is there any relationship between the two?",
       x = "GDP Per Capita in USD",
       y = "Life Expectancy in Years",
       caption = "Source: Gapminder") +
  theme_classic()

Alternatively, you can write your own theme using the theme() function.

mytheme <- theme_bw() +                   # We start with bw theme
  theme(
    axis.title = element_text(size=10),   # And overrite the paramaters
    axis.text = element_text(size=10),
    legend.title = element_text(size=10),
    legend.text = element_text(size=10)
    )

ggplot(data = gm_df,
       mapping = aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(color="indianred3") +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(title = "Economic Growth and Life Expectancy",
       subtitle = "Is there any relationship between the two?",
       x = "GDP Per Capita in USD",
       y = "Life Expectancy in Years",
       caption = "Source:") +
  mytheme
